## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Breaking Changes

| API | .NET 8 Behavior |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by the runtime |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to preserve original behavior
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async-native overload with cooperative cancellation
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

1. **No hard abort exists** — `Task.Run` won't forcibly kill stuck work. The `work` delegate must check `CancellationToken` cooperatively. If it calls uncancellable I/O, it will leak a background task.

2. **`Task.Run` + `Wait` can deadlock** on UI/ASP.NET sync contexts. Prefer the `async` overload. If you must stay sync, use `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` on a threadpool thread only.

3. **Exception wrapping changed** — `Task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`. The `catch` filter above re-wraps with a single inner exception to match the original behavior.

4. **`default(T)` is never returned on timeout** — the original code had a subtle bug: `thread.Abort()` would throw `TimeoutException`, but `result` could briefly hold a partial/default value. The new code avoids this entirely since `Task.Result` is only accessed on success.

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync (backward-compatible signature)
var val = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeExpensiveThing(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async with cooperative cancellation (preferred)
var val = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct =>
    {
        await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);  // respects cancellation
        return ProcessResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**Bottom line:** Replace `Thread.Abort` with `CancellationToken`. There is no equivalent to hard-abort in .NET 8 — design work delegates to poll cancellation tokens at natural checkpoints.
